<br>
See, this is an intriguing thought.<br>
<br>
Modern PWR's like the Westinghouse AP-1000 are very small compared to the behemoths we used to build.  (Seismic building volume 45 pecent less.)  So, it should be very possible to tear down an old reactor plant and build a new one on the same footprint that has twice the power output.  Plus, the AP-1000 is designed to safety levels that allow the theoretical elimination of the exclusion zone around the plant.  So, assume we reduce the exclusion area by half.  We could then quadruple the capacity of the existing nuclear sites.<br>
<br>
In the US, that could take the percentage of electricity generated by nuclear power from 19 percent or so to 76 percent.  This could COMPLETELY DISPLACE coal generation of electricity!!  With NO new sites needed!  No NIMBY idiocy!<br>
<br>
<br>
Plus, coal sites are pretty darn toxic, with the godawful ash heaps, I can't envision a nuclear plant actually being dirtier.  We could re-use old coal-plant sites to build nuclear plants/energy amps for the next five hundred years and add no more pollution than we already have out there.<br>
<br>
